In [43]:
def viz_predict_prob_surface(a_mod, input_df):
  
    viz_df = input_df.copy()
    
    viz_df['pred_prob'] = a_mod.predict( input_df )
    
    sns.relplot(data = viz_df, x='temp', y='season', col='overtime', hue='pred_prob',
                palette='icefire')
    
    plt.show()

In [45]:
viz_predict_prob_surface(fit_03, input_grid)

According to my two best models, it appears as if model 1 in the prediction grid is only split based off of the overtime input with a higher predicted probability if the game went into overtime.

On the flip side there is much more variation with model 3, as there is more impact by the other variables in season and temp. The highest prediction probability comes when there is overtime, the temperature is on the lower end.

Comparing Models¶

In [148]:
def extract_model_performance(a_mod, a_name, num_folds):
    res = pd.DataFrame({'mean_test_score': a_mod.cv_results_['mean_test_score'],
                        'std_test_score': a_mod.cv_results_['std_test_score']})
    
    res['mean_test_score_se'] = res.std_test_score / np.sqrt( num_folds )
    
    res['model_name'] = a_name
    
    res.drop(['std_test_score'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    res_best = res.loc[ res.mean_test_score == res.mean_test_score.max(), :].copy()
    
    return res_best

The performance metric appropriate to compare the models is the average performance score. The proper validation scheme for classification problems like mine is the StratifiedKFold cross validation. According to those metrics, the two statsmodels performed well against advanced models like Gradient Boosted Trees model and Support Vector Machine. The worst performing model by far was the Random Forest model. Further analysis can speak as to why this may be, but for this particular input we will advance to visualizing the best model which statistically was the Gradient Boosted Trees model on average.

We will now visualize on the grid ranked by the Random Forest import feature rankings. The most import features according to Random Forest was temp, wind, and defense_ave_yards_gained_pass. I am not surprised by these rankings as if I were to think back to football and not purely statistics, temperature, wind speed, and how well a defense can guard against the pass feels accurate for significant factors on whether or not a game will reach its implied total. Aside from temp this is pretty inconsistent with my statsmodels best models significant features as those top 3 were temp, season, and overtime.

def rf_viz_predict_prob_surface(a_mod, input_df):
  
    viz_df = input_df.copy()
    
    viz_df['pred_prob'] = a_mod.predict( input_df )
    
    sns.relplot(data = viz_df, x='temp', y='wind', col='defense_ave_yards_gained_pass', hue='pred_prob',
                palette='icefire')
    
    plt.show()
